def SCP682():
    print("Name: SCP-682")
    print("Class: Keter")
    print("Description: SCP-682 is a large, \nvaguely reptile-like creature of unknown origin. It appears to be extremely intelligent, \nand was observed to engage in complex communication with SCP-079 during their limited time of exposure. SCP-682 appears to have a hatred of all life, \nwhich has been expressed in several interviews during containment.\n")
def SCP079():
    print("Name: SCP-079")
    print("Class: Euclid")
    print("SCP-079 is an Exidy Sorcerer microcomputer built in 1978. In 1981, its owner, █████ ██████ (deceased), \na college sophomore attending ███, took it upon himself to attempt to code an AI. According to his notes, \n his plan was for the code to continuously evolve and improve itself as time went on. His project was completed a few months later, and after some tests and tweaks, \n █████ lost interest and moved on to a different brand of microcomputer. \n He left SCP-079 in his cluttered garage, still plugged in, and forgot about it for the next five years.\n")
def SCP173():
    print("Name: SCP-173")
    print("Class: Euclid")
    print("Description: Moved to Site-19 1993. Origin is as of yet unknown. It is constructed from concrete and rebar with traces of Krylon brand spray paint. \nSCP-173 is animate and extremely hostile. The object cannot move while within a direct line of sight. Line of sight must not be broken at any time with SCP-173. \nPersonnel assigned to enter container are instructed to alert one another before blinking. Object is reported to attack by snapping the neck at the base of the skull, \nor by strangulation. In the event of an attack, personnel are to observe Class 4 hazardous object containment procedures.\n")

def SCP012():
    print("Name: SCP-012")
    print("Class: Euclid")
    print("Description: SCP-012 was retrieved by Archaeologist K.M. Sandoval during the excavation of a northern Italian tomb destroyed in a recent storm. \nThe object, a piece of handwritten musical score entitled \"On Mount Golgotha\", part of a larger set of sheet music, appears to be incomplete. The red/black ink, first thought to be some form of berry or natural dye ink, \nwas later found to be human blood from multiple subjects. The first personnel to locate the sheet (Site 19 Special Salvage) \nhad two (2) members descend into insanity, attempting to use their own blood to finish the composition, ultimately resulting in massive blood loss and internal trauma \n")
